postcontent: This Rifle is a Springfield Armory M1 Garand mfg. circa Sept 1943. It's chambered in 30-06 and comes with (1) en-bloc clip and the CMP Certificate of Authenticity in a plastic hard case. This particular Rifle appears to be one of the guns that was lent to Denmark after WWII due to the fact of the "Rack Number" on the bottom of the buttstock. Since Denmark was occupied during the war, it is not a "Lend Lease" gun and therefore has NO IMPORT MARKS> It has a ME reading of 3 and a TE reading of 3 also which puts it well within the parameters of being a great shooter. The gun has been through an arsenal rebuild and it was re-barreled in early 1952 as the photos show. The wood shows marks from military use, but has no major issues such as chips, splits or cracks. This Rifle is a great collectable "War Horse" that certainly saw action in WWII and would fit great into a Military collection. It's a great nostalgic shooter and a real piece of American History
